/span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">maintained</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and independent schools and colleges throughout the UK. ASCL has members in more than 90 per cent of secondary schools and colleges o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f all types, responsible for the education of more than four million young people. This places the association in a unique position to consider this issue from the viewpoint of the leaders of secondary schools and of colleges.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ASCL welcomes this inquiry as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a timely opportunity for much needed reflection on these policies.</span></p><h2 style="margin:24pt 0pt 12pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Academies</span></h2><h3 style="margin:18pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Positives</span></h3><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ASCL has never opposed the idea of academy schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and the majority of ASCL members now lead academies. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ASCL members also lead</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the majority of colleges (FE and sixth f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">orm) and independents schools affiliated with HMC, GSA and the Society of Heads, the situations of which are in many ways similar t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that of academies.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a name="_Ref375043826"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ASCL has always argued in favour of subsidiarity: decisions being made at the ‘lowest’ level possible co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nsistent with efficient use of resources. This implies a greater degree of autonomy than schools have traditionally enjoyed, even after the introduction of local management of schools in the 1990s.</span></a></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Most ASCL members value extra freedom for them and their g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overnors to make decisions in the interests of their students</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. In the view of ASCL they are better placed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">than either local or central government </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to make such decisions. When policies are made remotely, and by officials however intelligent and well-meaning</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> who do not have to operate them on a daily basis with real children, they often result in waste and poor outcomes.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The academy project has on the whole been successful in the sense that the majority of schools in the secondary sector ar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e now academies. An</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ecoming an academy has helped some schools to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">make </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">significant improvement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. But by no means</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> all academies have been successful, nor have all the successful maintained schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">chosen to become academies. The picture is very complex, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">very different </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n different parts of the country</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:18pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Concerns</span></h3><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While ASCL is generally positive about </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">academies t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">here are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a number of contrary </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or complicating </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">factors which should be taken into account when considering the academy project in detail: </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While many </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">school </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">leaders</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have been content for their schools to leave local authority ownership, a significant minority, whose local authorities are more effective and supportive, have resisted this.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Many, supported by their governors and local communities, continue to do </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">so.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Note the caveat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in paragraph </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> above</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">; there are some issues that do require regulation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or decisions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that are binding over a wider area</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, if there is not to be w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">asteful duplication, gaps in provision, bad practice driving out good, and a lack of coherence in the public service.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a danger of atomisation, with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the most vulnerable young people being lost, along with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the concept of a public education service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in a welter of competing schools. The great majority of school leaders do not want that and continue exercise system leadership, both individually by working outside their own institution more or less formally, and via the policies they steer their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">school </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">academy towards.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ASCL has long encouraged partnership between schools and colleges of all kinds, and continues to do so. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This can help to recreate a sense of wider community and commitment to the best education for all. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In our experience this is most </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">effective when entered into freely as a ‘bottom up’ initiative</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, which of course is more likely when schools have greater autonomy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. There is no reason why </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">partnership working </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">not continue in the academy era, but if it is to be as effective and widesp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">read as it can be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">neither </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">regulation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> nor </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">accountability systems</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">discourage it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, as they often do now</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Leaders in schools of all kinds see themselves as primarily accountable to the children that attend the school and their parents. That is right, but</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> there is also a need to account for the use of public funds, and to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">take responsibility for the loc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">al education system as a whole.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">13</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are also many open questions about who should decide if intervention is needed in a failing academy, how such decision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s can be made, and what support can then be made available. See the discussion of a possible ‘middle tier’ in paragraphs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">18</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">19</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> below.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:18pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Process of change</span></h3><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">14</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While the concept of academy schools has been welcomed by a majority of school leaders, there has been concern about </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">how </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the change to academy status takes place. Those sc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hools that freely chose to become academies, ‘converter academies’, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are generally content, many of those </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">schools </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that had, or felt they had, no choice are less so. </span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">15</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ASCL would strongly urge that decisions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">about change of school status </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uld be taken by sc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hool governing bodies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and not under duress. The drive to move schools to academy status has become a policy imperative, and there have been cases of the DfE effectively forcing schools to become academies. This has especially applied to schools in more challenging areas (‘con</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">strained schools’) that have failed to reach arbitrary floor targets. Other routes to improving schools in such situations have worked </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">well </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in some instances and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">when favoured locally </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should be given more consideration.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:18pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Organisation</span></h3><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">16</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some sponsors, especia</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lly when schools have had little or no choice of sponsor, have added no value while taking funds from the school budget, and in a few cases have imposed eccentric ideas of their own with little regard to educational thinking or educational values. There is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a need to impose stricter conditions on what organisations can become sponsors. On the whole, the system has worked best when sponsors have been other educational institutions (other schools, colleges, universities).</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">17</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ASCL would urge that school governing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bodies should decide whether on becoming an academy their school should have a sponsor, and choose the sponsor if there is to be one.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">18</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a name="_Ref375047378"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As the majority of secondary schools are now academies, and more are following suit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> there is a question about the capacit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y of the DfE and the EFA to support and fund them. It is generally accepted that it is not good practice to run significant numbers of local organisations directly from Whitehall. That raises a question of what types of organisation should be put in place </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(either by government or by the schools themselves) to be a ‘middle tier’ between national government and individual academies.</span></a></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">19</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><a name="_Ref375047381"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a danger that these ch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">anges will effectively remove local authoritie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s from education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, not replace them,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">so </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">actually</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> centralise the system. The Secretary of State for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Education </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">needs to adopt a self-denying ordinance to prevent himself (and so far as possible his successors) from interference in decisions that should be better taken at lower levels.</span></a></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">20</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are still some</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> uncertainties about the regulations under which academies work. For example, the question of who is the employer of staff in a school should be clear, it should be the governing body, but some trades unions are continuing to take national action in such s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">chools in dispute with the Secretary of State.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">21</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The regulation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, accountability and funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of academies and schools of other kinds (and so</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> far as possible colleges) need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to be brought into better alignment. There remain a number of anomalies.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:18pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Chains</span></h3><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">22</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Again </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ASCL does not oppose </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">chains </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">per se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and some are working well. However, some have imposed great restriction on local decision-making, making the governing body, head teacher and other leaders follow a ‘formula’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or imposing policies decided by the chain. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">his works against the principle of subsidiarity, leaves local leadership in some cases with less freedom than when </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">maintain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed by a local authority, and raises questions about the accountability of chains.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">23</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some chains have blocked local partnership working </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by requiring their schools to partner only with other members of the chain, often at a distance. In some cases this has prevented potentially valuable local partnerships from forming at all.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">24</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On the whole it is the smaller chains, and those with a more loca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l focus, that are seen as of value by local school leaders of the academies that make them up. Those that are larger and have schools in widely separated locations are seen as more controlling, less supportive and less accountable.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">25</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a place for cha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ins of academies, but ASCL would not see them as the norm, or the answer to the ‘middle tier’ question.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:24pt 0pt 12pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Free schools</span></h2><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">26</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Again ASCL does not oppose the idea of free schools as such. At present</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> once a free school is established it becomes an academy like any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">other. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are many issues, however, about the way that the free schools policy has been promoted, the way free schools have come into being, and the lack of planning or sufficiently effective regulation.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">27</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The key issue is how free schools are agreed. The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">re has been little attempt so far to consider the effect of setting up a free school in a locality on the schools that already serve it, and on the local education system as a whole. Where there is a shortage of places setting up a free school might well b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e a sensible move, but where there is a surplus of places consideration should be given to diseconomies of scale. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f the establishment of a free school leads to other schools closing there will be expensive public buildings surplus to requirement. And</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mos</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t importantly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">young people will certainly suffer while such a shaking out is taking place.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">28</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The free school policy has undermined attempts to plan school places. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is accepted that f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or there to be parental choice there must be some surplus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> places, but these surplus places are expensive, and a charge upon the public purse. They therefore need to be as few as compatible with reasonable choice, but in some cases free schools have been agreed in areas that already have a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">large </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">surplus of places</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">29</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a great deal of resentment amongst school leaders of existing schools of all kinds about the favourable funding that free schools have received. Significant capital sums have been devoted to setting up new schools, when in some cases those nearb</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y have a longstanding unmet need for capital spending to make their buildings fit for purpose.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">30</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Likewise, revenue funding of free schools to planned numbers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> when their places have often not been filled has meant their pupils being funded at higher rates than in nearby schools struggling with very tight budgets. A period of austerity is not a good time for such an experiment.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> There is a need to quickly bring f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ree school funding into alignment with a fair funding formula that we hope to see for all publicly funded schools.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">31</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Even more than for academy sponsors, much greater ‘vetting’ of free school sponsors is required. There have already been instances of free sc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hools being set up for reasons that have little to do with education by groups that not only lack educational expertise but make no effort to acquire any. Such schools will fail, and will damage children’s education and life chances while doing so.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">32</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some fr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ee schools will no doubt succeed, and join the family of schools in their area. Their leaders are also mostly ASCL members. Such schools will in a few years be little different</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> from the academies around them.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">33</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I hope that this is of value to your inquiry, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ASCL is willing to be further consulted and to assist in any way that it can.</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>